         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">With a mind strong as diamond and powerful, he made the most excellent wish for the irreversible Buddhahood.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... finally he did not forget the with for Buddhahood. And in addition || In the tune Apsaradarśana: ||</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>315</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>229</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1970"/><citedRange>272</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... who, being worried by the suffering, did not forsake friendship, who did forget (the wish for) Buddhahood, (he received the name Maitreya. ||)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... At the time when there was a king named Vāsava, then the Buddha-god of gods Ratnaśikhin ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>308</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">When the live of beings will be eighty thousand years long, (in a world) of happiness ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... in forty mahākalpas he made manifest the meditation of friendship.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>405</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:kolver1965"/><citedRange>137</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... after having emitted before ... The four hundred and ninety five</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>251</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(bodhisattvas would appeared later.) ... the water (of the Gāṅga river), as it were, in the whole Madhyadeśa.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... there he went (to the Dakṣināpatha) and there also (he astonished many sages, starting) from Bādhari the brahmin.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... having heard the appearance (of the Buddha-god, the teacher,) in the world</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>295</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(In the tune of ... ): || (He is) not satisfied with goodness, shying away from falsehood.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>234</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... having the name of successor, he now leaves from home toward the Buddha-god, o Pūrṇaka.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Therefore, it is said: "The first son will, after a short time, be the successor of the king. (He will be a very bad being),</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1976a"/><citedRange>78</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the one who does not see this noble Maitreya and this one, despite being alive, will be deemed dead.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... in all (of his) births his dignity has become manifest ...now the leaving from home of the noble Maitreya ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>345</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... because of the great feast of consecration for successorship, from now for a thousand years</seg></seg></choice></p>
