               <item n="m_translation_old">a1 With a mind strong as diamond and powerful, he made the most excellent wish for the irreversible Buddhahood.
a2 ... finally he did not forget the with for Buddhahood. And in addition || In the tune Apsaradarśana: ||
a3 ... who, being worried by the suffering, did not forsake friendship, who did forget (the wish for) Buddhahood, (he received the name Maitreya. ||)
a4 ... At the time when there was a king named Vāsava, then the Buddha-god of gods Ratnaśikhin ...
a5 When the live of beings will be eighty thousand years long, (in a world) of happiness ...
a6 ... in forty mahākalpas he made manifest the meditation of friendship.
a7 ... after having emitted before ... The four hundred and ninety five
a8 (bodhisattvas would appeared later.) ... the water (of the Gāṅga river), as it were, in the whole Madhyadeśa.
b1 ... there he went (to the Dakṣināpatha) and there also (he astonished many sages, starting) from Bādhari the brahmin.
b2 ... having heard the appearance (of the Buddha-god, the teacher,) in the world
b3 (In the tune of ... ): || (He is) not satisfied with goodness, shying away from falsehood.
b4 ... having the name of successor, he now leaves from home toward the Buddha-god, o Pūrṇaka.
b5 ... Therefore, it is said: "The first son will, after a short time, be the successor of the king. (He will be a very bad being),
b6 the one who does not see this noble Maitreya and this one, despite being alive, will be deemed dead.
b7 ... in all (of his) births his dignity has become manifest ...now the leaving from home of the noble Maitreya ...
b8 ... because of the great feast of consecration for successorship, from now for a thousand years</item>
